{"url": "https://www.reddit.com/r/learnprogramming/comments/9bwde5/remote_db_vs_installed_on_server/", "text": "Hi, I am a beginner and recently I deployed a node js app using a digital ocean droplet. I am connecting to mongoDB which is hosted on mlab. I was just wondering if it would be better to install mongoDB on the server?\nThanks in advance :)", "score": 2, "comments": [{"body": "You should leave them separate. Makes scaling easier and it ensures any weird quirks about remote requests are nipped early on.  \n\n\nIn terms of pricing, Droplet and MongoDB will essentially scale the same. You're not super likely to have a Node JS application get so popular that you exceed the free MongoDB limit. Nor are you likely to make a major impact on the storage capacity of Droplet.  \n\n\nYour worst case scenario is somehow hacks your server and gets admin control. Then they get access to your DB which would compromise usernames and passwords. Even with salting and hashing, full admin control pretty much fucks a DB. ", "id": "e5681cg", "replies": []}], "title": "Remote DB vs installed on server"}